{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016JhkmYtq5sxbeGQ5C2Auam","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tid: \"PRD-542.1\"\n3\ttitle: \"Timeout resolution module with effort-based mapping\"\n4\tkind: task\n5\tstatus: ready\n6\tpriority: medium\n7\teffort: s\n8\tcapability: simple\n9\tparent: \"[[PRD-542-effort-based-agent-timeouts]]\"\n10\tdepends_on: []\n11\tblocks:\n12\t  - \"[[PRD-542.2-integrate-timeout-into-runner]]\"\n13\timpacts:\n14\t  - src/darkfactory/timeouts.py\n15\t  - .darkfactory/config.toml\n16\t  - tests/test_timeouts.py\n17\tworkflow: null\n18\ttarget_version: null\n19\tcreated: 2026-04-08\n20\tupdated: 2026-04-08\n21\ttags:\n22\t  - harness\n23\t---\n24\t\n25\t# Timeout resolution module with effort-based mapping\n26\t\n27\t## Summary\n28\t\n29\tCreate a new `darkfactory/timeouts.py` module exposing a pure function `resolve_timeout(prd, config, cli_override) -> int` that computes the agent task timeout in seconds. The function implements a clear resolution order: CLI flag > PRD frontmatter `timeout_minutes` > config table lookup by effort × capability multiplier > built-in defaults. This task also adds the config schema for the timeout table in `.darkfactory/config.toml` and comprehensive unit tests.\n30\t\n31\t## Requirements\n32\t\n33\t1. Create `src/darkfactory/timeouts.py` with a `resolve_timeout()` function.\n34\t2. Built-in default effort → timeout mapping:\n35\t   - `xs` → 300s (5 min)\n36\t   - `s` → 600s (10 min)\n37\t   - `m` → 1200s (20 min)\n38\t   - `l` → 2400s (40 min)\n39\t   - `xl` → 4500s (75 min)\n40\t3. Capability multiplier applied on top of effort base: `simple` ×1.0, `moderate` ×1.25, `complex` ×1.5. When `capability` is `trivial` or missing, use ×1.0.\n41\t4. Resolution order (highest priority wins):\n42\t   - `cli_override` (integer minutes, if provided)\n43\t   - PRD frontmatter `timeout_minutes` field (integer minutes)\n44\t   - Config table lookup (`[timeouts]` section in `.darkfactory/config.toml`) by effort × capability multiplier\n45\t   - Built-in defaults × capability multiplier\n46\t5. The function returns an integer (seconds) and a string describing the source (e.g. `\"cli\"`, `\"prd_frontmatter\"`, `\"config\"`, `\"default\"`).\n47\t6. Add a `[timeouts]` section to `.darkfactory/config.toml` schema with keys for each effort tier (values in minutes) and capability multipliers.\n48\t7. If the PRD has no `effort` field, fall back to `s` (10 min) as the default.\n49\t\n50\t## Technical Approach\n51\t\n52\t### `src/darkfactory/timeouts.py`\n53\t\n54\t```python\n55\tDEFAULT_EFFORT_TIMEOUTS = {\n56\t    \"xs\": 300,\n57\t    \"s\": 600,\n58\t    \"m\": 1200,\n59\t    \"l\": 2400,\n60\t    \"xl\": 4500,\n61\t}\n62\t\n63\tCAPABILITY_MULTIPLIERS = {\n64\t    \"trivial\": 1.0,\n65\t    \"simple\": 1.0,\n66\t    \"moderate\": 1.25,\n67\t    \"complex\": 1.5,\n68\t}\n69\t\n70\tdef resolve_timeout(\n71\t    effort: str | None,\n72\t    capability: str | None,\n73\t    timeout_minutes_frontmatter: int | None,\n74\t    config_timeouts: dict | None,\n75\t    cli_override: int | None,\n76\t) -> tuple[int, str]:\n77\t    \"\"\"Return (timeout_seconds, source_description).\"\"\"\n78\t    ...\n79\t```\n80\t\n81\t### Config schema addition (`.darkfactory/config.toml`)\n82\t\n83\t```toml\n84\t[timeouts]\n85\txs = 5       # minutes\n86\ts = 10\n87\tm = 20\n88\tl = 40\n89\txl = 75\n90\t\n91\t[timeouts.capability_multipliers]\n92\ttrivial = 1.0\n93\tsimple = 1.0\n94\tmoderate = 1.25\n95\tcomplex = 1.5\n96\t```\n97\t\n98\t### Unit tests (`tests/test_timeouts.py`)\n99\t\n100\tTable-driven tests covering:\n101\t- Every effort tier with default mapping\n102\t- Every capability multiplier\n103\t- PRD frontmatter override takes precedence over config/defaults\n104\t- CLI override takes precedence over everything\n105\t- Config table overrides built-in defaults\n106\t- Missing effort falls back to `s`\n107\t- Missing capability uses multiplier 1.0\n108\t\n109\t## Acceptance Criteria\n110\t\n111\t- [ ] AC-1: `resolve_timeout()` returns correct seconds for each effort tier using built-in defaults.\n112\t- [ ] AC-2: Capability multiplier is applied correctly on top of effort base.\n113\t- [ ] AC-3: PRD frontmatter `timeout_minutes` overrides computed value.\n114\t- [ ] AC-4: CLI override (minutes) overrides everything.\n115\t- [ ] AC-5: Config table values override built-in defaults.\n116\t- [ ] AC-6: Function returns both timeout value and source string.\n117\t- [ ] AC-7: Unit tests cover all resolution paths with table-driven tests.\n118\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"939fc375-8ed1-4dc0-8515-8b3ee2d79451","uuid":"5ad03249-eefb-4c38-9bd0-25fc1d56f82e","timestamp":"2026-04-09T02:37:20.197Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/sksizer2/Developer/DarkFactory/.worktrees/PRD-222-general-purpose-tool/prds/PRD-542.1-timeout-resolution-module.md","content":"---\nid: \"PRD-542.1\"\ntitle: \"Timeout resolution module with effort-based mapping\"\nkind: task\nstatus: ready\npriority: medium\neffort: s\ncapability: simple\nparent: \"[[PRD-542-effort-based-agent-timeouts]]\"\ndepends_on: []\nblocks:\n  - \"[[PRD-542.2-integrate-timeout-into-runner]]\"\nimpacts:\n  - src/darkfactory/timeouts.py\n  - .darkfactory/config.toml\n  - tests/test_timeouts.py\nworkflow: null\ntarget_version: null\ncreated: 2026-04-08\nupdated: 2026-04-08\ntags:\n  - harness\n---\n\n# Timeout resolution module with effort-based mapping\n\n## Summary\n\nCreate a new `darkfactory/timeouts.py` module exposing a pure function `resolve_timeout(prd, config, cli_override) -> int` that computes the agent task timeout in seconds. The function implements a clear resolution order: CLI flag > PRD frontmatter `timeout_minutes` > config table lookup by effort × capability multiplier > built-in defaults. This task also adds the config schema for the timeout table in `.darkfactory/config.toml` and comprehensive unit tests.\n\n## Requirements\n\n1. Create `src/darkfactory/timeouts.py` with a `resolve_timeout()` function.\n2. Built-in default effort → timeout mapping:\n   - `xs` → 300s (5 min)\n   - `s` → 600s (10 min)\n   - `m` → 1200s (20 min)\n   - `l` → 2400s (40 min)\n   - `xl` → 4500s (75 min)\n3. Capability multiplier applied on top of effort base: `simple` ×1.0, `moderate` ×1.25, `complex` ×1.5. When `capability` is `trivial` or missing, use ×1.0.\n4. Resolution order (highest priority wins):\n   - `cli_override` (integer minutes, if provided)\n   - PRD frontmatter `timeout_minutes` field (integer minutes)\n   - Config table lookup (`[timeouts]` section in `.darkfactory/config.toml`) by effort × capability multiplier\n   - Built-in defaults × capability multiplier\n5. The function returns an integer (seconds) and a string describing the source (e.g. `\"cli\"`, `\"prd_frontmatter\"`, `\"config\"`, `\"default\"`).\n6. Add a `[timeouts]` section to `.darkfactory/config.toml` schema with keys for each effort tier (values in minutes) and capability multipliers.\n7. If the PRD has no `effort` field, fall back to `s` (10 min) as the default.\n\n## Technical Approach\n\n### `src/darkfactory/timeouts.py`\n\n```python\nDEFAULT_EFFORT_TIMEOUTS = {\n    \"xs\": 300,\n    \"s\": 600,\n    \"m\": 1200,\n    \"l\": 2400,\n    \"xl\": 4500,\n}\n\nCAPABILITY_MULTIPLIERS = {\n    \"trivial\": 1.0,\n    \"simple\": 1.0,\n    \"moderate\": 1.25,\n    \"complex\": 1.5,\n}\n\ndef resolve_timeout(\n    effort: str | None,\n    capability: str | None,\n    timeout_minutes_frontmatter: int | None,\n    config_timeouts: dict | None,\n    cli_override: int | None,\n) -> tuple[int, str]:\n    \"\"\"Return (timeout_seconds, source_description).\"\"\"\n    ...\n```\n\n### Config schema addition (`.darkfactory/config.toml`)\n\n```toml\n[timeouts]\nxs = 5       # minutes\ns = 10\nm = 20\nl = 40\nxl = 75\n\n[timeouts.capability_multipliers]\ntrivial = 1.0\nsimple = 1.0\nmoderate = 1.25\ncomplex = 1.5\n```\n\n### Unit tests (`tests/test_timeouts.py`)\n\nTable-driven tests covering:\n- Every effort tier with default mapping\n- Every capability multiplier\n- PRD frontmatter override takes precedence over config/defaults\n- CLI override takes precedence over everything\n- Config table overrides built-in defaults\n- Missing effort falls back to `s`\n- Missing capability uses multiplier 1.0\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] AC-1: `resolve_timeout()` returns correct seconds for each effort tier using built-in defaults.\n- [ ] AC-2: Capability multiplier is applied correctly on top of effort base.\n- [ ] AC-3: PRD frontmatter `timeout_minutes` overrides computed value.\n- [ ] AC-4: CLI override (minutes) overrides everything.\n- [ ] AC-5: Config table values override built-in defaults.\n- [ ] AC-6: Function returns both timeout value and source string.\n- [ ] AC-7: Unit tests cover all resolution paths with table-driven tests.\n","numLines":118,"startLine":1,"totalLines":118}}}
